Thought_Process: This is a serial-dictatorship style process: when I am called, I get my highest-ranked remaining company. Since I do not know my random position, any attempt to "game" by moving a less-preferred but more-available company up would only risk choosing it even in cases where a more-preferred option (especially Company_A) is still available. Given others’ top choices (B targets Company_B, C targets Company_D, D/E target Company_C), Company_A is not the top choice of any other seeker but could still be taken by others if they pick later options; therefore I should keep my true order to always take the best available at my turn.

Because assignment is by random serial order with no company-side priorities used, the best strategy is to rank companies in my true preference order. Any misreport could cause me to pick a less-preferred company earlier when my top choice would have been available, and cannot improve my chance of getting a higher-ranked company since availability depends only on earlier seekers’ picks.

With random serial order and sequential choice from remaining companies, my best strategy is to rank companies truthfully. Any misreport (e.g., moving a safer option up) can only cause me to take a less-preferred company in cases where my top choice would still have been available, while it cannot improve my outcome when my top choices are already taken (I would then fall to the next available anyway). Given my true preferences and that all companies have one seat, submitting my true order maximizes my chance of getting the highest possible remaining company when it is my turn.

This is a serial dictatorship: when it is my turn I get the highest-ranked company still available from my submitted list. There is no benefit to misreporting because ranking a less-preferred company above a more-preferred one can only cause me to take the worse company in states where the better one would have been available. Therefore I should submit my true preference order to maximize my outcome for every possible serial position and prior picks.
